		<div class="qna-section">
			<div class="question">Question 2: How to prepare for the companies of that sector?</div>

			<div class="answer">Answer:My interest zone lies in embedded systems, firmware engineering, image processing etc. These are the domains where you see your softwares do wonders when they interface with state-of-the-art hardwares. To prepare for this sector you need to have a good amount of practical intuition of various electronics as well as software components. I suggest that you build up strong hold on C or C++, modern day microcontrollers, Git etc. Apart from this you are should have knowledge about topics like digital electronics, operating systems. You should always keep yourself engaged in robotics' projects so that you will be able to feel the programing languages the way an embedded or a firmware engineer is expected to. You should get a good understanding about the basic aspects of working of C/C++ which you can find in GFG. Having a good resume is a must if you want to enter automation sector. For robotics companies, I'll strongly suggest to dive into ROS.
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="qna-section">
			<div class="question">Question 3: Describe the selection procedure of that company.</div>

				<div class="answer">Answer: Mine was an off-campus placement process. I got to know about the opportunity from one of our club's senior of 2k12 batch. I emailed my resume to company's HR and after 10-15 days, got a phone call from the HR to schedule an interview. The topics which you need to focus on, depends on the company. I revised the core fundamentals of C language, memory management in OS and went through the DSP course which we studied in fifth semester. The interview was of about 1 Hr 20 min and was extensively based on C language.  
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="qna-section">
			<div class="question">Question  4:Now coming to the most dreaded part of every recruitment process, describe your interview(s)(include projects)</div>

			<div class="answer">Answer: 
			<ul style="margin-left:20px">
			<li>The long interview started with basics such as introduction with pannel and getting comfortable with the online environment. Firstly I was asked questions on Digital Signal Processing, ADCs and digital electronics followed by exhaustive programming language based  questions. The questions were related to structures, pointers, macros, memory layouts, logical operations, signal processing, multi-threading in Python. I was also asked few HR questions towards the end. So basically the whole interview was about being cool minded, focused and enjoying the process. You should not get frightened if you are not able to answer the questions thrown at you in the begining as you never know if the last few seconds of the interview might land you in your dream job. You never know the next second could bring you all the happiness.
			</div>
		</div>

		<div class="qna-section">
			<div class="question">Question 5:As you mentioned that projects played a vital role in your placement, what were the projects that you did?</div>

			<div class="answer">Answer:I have done around 5-6 significant projects. My favourites are the ABU-Robocon & an OpenCV based scanner which you could find in my GitHub repo. it is I guess world's first open source code to scan documents the same way CamScanner did. My contributions to dev of holonomic drives for Robocon bot proved to be my backbone for the placement processes. I have also spent a significant amount of time @ the Autonomous Systems Lab (ASL) in Mechanical Engg. Dept. There I worked on 3D-printers and a research project to control pneumatic cylinders which was then used by our team of Dr. Arun Udai & MTech students to develop a huge 6-DOF gaming platform. For the same project I also interned @ IIT-BHU in summers. Apart from these as a part of some awesome robotics competition we worked on stuffs like Augmented Reality etc. Self balancing robot or a mini-segway is another project which I'm very fond of. We used some innovative methods to make the segway perform fantastically. C based Tic-Tac-Toe & Matlab based speech recongnition were the first complete projects I did.
			</div>
